Q63: What robot arm? None is pictured. The study is about robot arms for assistive feeding.
1_Q49: The first arm segment looks really thin compared to the second arm segment. It feels like something that might break. It also looks weird, with the two joints being different (square vs. tubular/slender).
2_Q49: The robot arm is smooth, sleek, and curvy. It looks well-designed and is nice to look at. It does not have a sort of stark 'industrial' feel that one might expect of a robot.
3_Q49: This is a really weird mashup. The robot has a tubular curvy part and a square part? It looks like a frankenarm for no discernible reason. I would trust it less.
4_Q49: The robot arm has a seemingly random/superfluous bulge on one of its joints, which makes me think that it is engineered weirdly / not reliable / etc. It is a bit strange looking. I would expect such a weird design from a more budget robot arm.
5_Q49: It's bulbous! Why? It's like a MegaMan arm, so it's a little aggressive. And it looks very strange.
6_Q49: Similar to a previous arm, this robot has a seemingly random and superfluous bulge which influenced my answers.
7_Q49: The robot arm is boxy (which is less organic / a little more aggressive than rounded), but it has curvy joints. It seems less organic than one that is more tubular.
8_Q49: Both arm segments are consistent. They are round. They aren't weirdly bulgy or anything. It looks like it would be an effective arm.
9_Q49: This robot arm is boxier, so it seems a little more aggressive and less relaxing than the more curvy arm.
feedback:
Inconsistent arm segment design felt sloppy and made me feel less confident about the quality of the arm.
Too thin of an arm segment made me doubt the arm's strength.
Bulbous arm segments made me question _why_ is the arm bulbous, and reminded me of megaman's blaster.

Q63: An aid to help perform certain daily tasks such as eating.
1_Q49: Thinner bottom section that is concave towards it's center
3_Q49: Similar form to the one before but different texture/looks smoother and not glossy if I remember the previous one correctly.
4_Q49: Double thicc i think or thicc lower section with square head.
8_Q49: Circle head (? Srry.  Lack of a better term) than square
feedback: The thickness of the segments.   The ones that have a smaller diameter as you travel along the length of a segment has structural concerns.  But it also depends on material its made out of and what applications is said arm being uses it.  The ones where the diameter increases towards the center as you travel along the surface of a segment might have stress issues at the joins.  But again, materials used and applications of said arm must be considered.

Q63: A remote manipulation device,  ment to lift and manipulate things too heavy, awkward or dangerous or delicate for a human.
3_Q49: Segments look mismatched, lower arm makes it look awkward and fragile
funciton: A device used for manipulation used where a human cannot
feedback: The man segments of the arms and their geometry. Specifically curved vs angular design, and if the two segments felt "matched". The arm end had some influence but was much less noticable.

Q63: The robotic arm I am about to see is supposed to assist a human in eating food.
1_Q49: The four-prong socket piece at the end, the clearly stable positioning joints, and the base.
2_Q49: It feels a little more sleekly shaped, but I'm not sure what effect that would have on the structural integrity of the device.
3_Q49: Listen, most of these robot arms look about the same and would reasonably have the same internal components, and I don't think there's much difference between glossy and matte material paints in terms of cost.
4_Q49: This looks like it has more functional parts inside the middle part of the arm (hence the oval shape).
5_Q49: This one's more "bubbly" than the others, but it still looks pretty solid.
6_Q49: This looks nearly identical to one of the earlier ones, and I couldn't think of any major differences to rate that on.
7_Q49: Just like all the other arms I've seen so far, this one has what looks to be a pretty basic output point and reliable joints.
8_Q49: I feel like I'm losing my mind here, looking at nearly-identical feeding arms, but this one looks a little more simple than the other ones.
9_Q49: The bevel-square whatever angles on the arm pieces are a bit more awkward than the rounded ones, but couldn't make it less sturdy.
funciton: The initial summary said it was for assistive feeding. I assume the opening holes at the end are either tubes to move food for someone to consume, or they're sockets to put some sort of manipulator onto for holding utensils and bringing said utensils from the bowl or plate to the person's face, but I have no way of knowing for sure.
feedback: I had no idea how the end with the five holes in it is supposed to work. I'm assuming it's either a tube or a plug-in for some kind of tool-manipulating element. It looked like it was either solid plastic or painted metal elements, but none of the parts that would go into feeding points would be super expensive. I can't imagine, even at the upper limit, that parts wouldn't cost an insane amount of money.

Q63: To help people who have trouble eating with doing so
1_Q49: The color and tapering of the arm
funciton: To help people who can't eat feed themselves
feedback: The amount of curve in the arm top vs bottom as well as the shape of the face plate. Positive curvature on only the bottom seemed much more strange then double curvature or negative curvature, and as a result seemed less capable. Negative curvature seemed more awkward, but in a charming kind of way. Square face plates or arm shapes were more varied

Q63: To function similarly to that of a humans to preform tasks, but has a potentially greater range of motion/ability than a human’s
1_Q49: The skinny portion near the bottom
3_Q49: Body shape. Squared & tapered on the bottom.
4_Q49: The color scheme, how movable it looks, the connection “face”, sturdy looking base
funciton: The ability to preform tasks similar to a human arm, but with a wider possible range of capability
feedback: The one with the “round belly” was cute and made me giggle

Q63: Either as a freely-moving unit that assists humans via their reaching and ambulatory ability. OR As a cool robo-arm that is physically attached to a person as a prosthesis.
1_Q49: Lower arms shape gives look of frailty yet dexterity?
2_Q49: The curvy shapes of the arms seems more organic
3_Q49: the lower arm's shape is more organic and pleasing to the eye
4_Q49: Same as before, the lower arms shape make it appear strong and capable.
5_Q49: shape of the forarm and lower give a look of strength
6_Q49: It's posture and positioning of the overall arm. The contours of the lower arm give it a sapien-look.
7_Q49: The thinness of the arm structure. Lanky guy
8_Q49: Smooth simplicity in the shape of the arm bars
9_Q49: Seems more restricted at the elbow joint?
funciton: To manipulate objects around it's immediate environment
feedback: The arm bars, specifically the lower section, seemed to stand out most when various shapes changed. A thicker build felt sturdier, and a thinner one felt more delicate and dexterous. A curvy, mat finish felt organic, while a blocky shape and shiny materials felt modern and out of reach of the everyday consumer.
